 To implement backup and disaster recovery for Azure Functions, you can follow these steps based on the provided context:

1. Create an active/passive failover configuration for Durable Functions using Traffic Manager [Source: azure/Azure Functions/Disaster recovery and geo-distribution in Durable Functions > General considerations]. The primary function app will handle HTTP requests, while the backup function app will take over when the primary app fails.

2. Configure the storage account and task hub in the primary region for both function apps to share [Source: azure/Azure Functions/Disaster recovery and geo-distribution in Durable Functions > General considerations]. All function apps that are redundantly deployed must share the same function access keys when they're activated via HTTP.

3. Implement a backup strategy for your functions using Azure Storage or other storage providers [Source: azure/Azure Functions/Disaster recovery and geo-distribution in Durable Functions > General considerations]. For example, you can use the `BackupSiteContent` sample provided in the context to back up files from a storage account.

   - In JavaScript (PM3), create an Azure Function named `E2_GetFileList` using the following code:
     ```javascript
     // function.json
     {
       "scriptFile": "__init__.js",
       "bindings": [
         {
           "name": "myQueueItem",
           "type": "queueTrigger",
           "direction": "in",
           "queueName": "myqueue-items",
           "connection": "MyStorageConnection"
         }
       ]
     }
     ```
     ```javascript
     // index.js
     const { ActivityClient } = require("@azure/durable-functions");
     const { Client } = require("readdirp");

     let client;

     module.exports = async function (context, myQueueItem) {
       if (!client) {
         client = new Client({
           root: "path/to/your/storage",
           depth: Infinity,
           fileFilter: /\.(txt|pdf)$/,
           onError: (err) => console.error(err),
         });
       }

       const results = await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
         client.on("entry", (entry) => {
           entry.file.stat((err, stat) => {
             if (err) return reject(err);
             context.bindings.outputBlob = entry.file;
             context.bindings.outputBlob.metadata.backupTime = new Date();
             context.bindings.outputBlob.openWrite((err, outputFile) => {
               if (err) return reject(err);
               outputFile.write("Backup of " + entry.name, (err) => {
                 if (err) return reject(err);
                 resolve();
               });
             });
           });
         });

         client.on("error", (err) => {
           console.error(err);
           reject(err);
         });
       });

       context.log("Backup completed");
     };
     ```

4. Test the function locally and deploy it to Azure [Source: azure/Azure Functions/Quickstart: Create a TypeScript Durable Functions app > Test the function locally]. Use Azure Functions Core Tools to run the project on your local development computer, then provide the URL endpoint of your HTTP-triggered function.

5. Configure Traffic Manager to route traffic between the primary and backup function apps based on priority [Source: azure/Azure Functions/Disaster recovery and geo-distribution in Durable Functions > General considerations]. For more information, see [Priority traffic-routing method](../../traffic-manager/traffic-manager-routing-methods.md#priority-traffic-routing-method).

